a decent bowel movement...

83
00:00:13,121 --> 00:00:15,089
since
the Reagan administration.

84
00:00:15,123 --> 00:00:17,648
OK.

85
00:00:17,692 --> 00:00:19,626
[Baseball game on TV]

86
00:00:19,660 --> 00:00:22,094
So, are you ever going to
tell me about that baseball?

87
00:00:22,130 --> 00:00:23,358
No.

88
00:00:23,398 --> 00:00:24,956
[Mechanical whir]

89
00:00:24,999 --> 00:00:27,593
[Machine beeping]

90
00:00:31,139 --> 00:00:32,766
Come on, Lucille.

91
00:00:32,807 --> 00:00:34,604
Don't die on me now.

92
00:00:34,642 --> 00:00:37,440
Daddy knows you're tired...

93
00:00:37,478 --> 00:00:41,676
but daddy also knows
you got another few in you.

94
00:00:41,716 --> 00:00:43,946
Yes, you do.

95
00:00:43,985 --> 00:00:45,543
Do you really think that works?

96
00:00:45,586 --> 00:00:47,281
Sometimes,
but when it doesn't...

97
00:00:47,321 --> 00:00:48,811
you give her
a little love tap.

98
00:00:48,856 --> 00:00:49,982
[Clunk]

99
00:00:50,024 --> 00:00:51,389
[Machine whirs]

100
00:00:54,162 --> 00:00:55,322
Uhh.

101
00:00:57,532 --> 00:00:59,363
Good morning, Jackie.

102
00:00:59,400 --> 00:01:00,833
JACKIE: Good morning.

103
00:01:07,075 --> 00:01:08,406
Uh, Gibbons?

104
00:01:09,610 --> 00:01:10,838
I need you in here, please.

105
00:01:12,613 --> 00:01:13,978
HIGGINS: You've done
excellent work here...

106
00:01:14,015 --> 00:01:16,108
and now let me
ask you a question.

107
00:01:16,150 --> 00:01:18,345
What does Reebok stand for?

108
00:01:18,386 --> 00:01:21,913
Um, I believe the Reebok
is a type ofAfrican gazelle.

109
00:01:21,956 --> 00:01:24,550
[Loud whirring]

110
00:01:24,592 --> 00:01:30,792
No. Reebok stands
for credibility and prestige.

111
00:01:30,832 --> 00:01:34,290
We are going global.

112
00:01:34,335 --> 00:01:35,427
Wheatgrass?

113
00:01:35,470 --> 00:01:37,563
I'll pass.

114
00:01:37,605 --> 00:01:38,731
Reebok wants us to do...

115
00:01:38,773 --> 00:01:41,571
their female 'tweens
footwear campaign.

116
00:01:41,609 --> 00:01:44,100
-'Tweens?
-'Tweens, Gibbons--

117
00:01:44,145 --> 00:01:47,376
for females between their
adolescence and teen years.

118
00:01:47,415 --> 00:01:48,609
Get with it, Gibbons.

119
00:01:48,649 --> 00:01:49,877
Ohh. Jackie,
could you come in here, please?

120
00:01:49,917 --> 00:01:52,909
Mr. Higgins, this is such
a great opportunity for me.

121
00:01:52,954 --> 00:01:54,080
I don't know what to say.

122
00:01:54,122 --> 00:01:56,283
Well, then don't say anything.
I might change my mind.

123
00:01:56,324 --> 00:01:57,450
You wanted to see me?

124
00:01:57,492 --> 00:01:59,756
Yes. How's the Reebok campaign
coming along?

125
00:01:59,794 --> 00:02:00,920
Excellent, sir.

126
00:02:00,962 --> 00:02:04,022
I haven't completed the concept
yet, but I'm close.

127
00:02:04,065 --> 00:02:07,000
Well, you just got
a little bit closer.

128
00:02:07,034 --> 00:02:10,367
Gibbons here
is joining the creative team.

129
00:02:10,404 --> 00:02:11,530
Hmm.

130
00:02:11,572 --> 00:02:15,008
KEVIN: OK, Reebok.

131
00:02:15,042 --> 00:02:19,411
All right.
We have two baby chickens...

132
00:02:19,447 --> 00:02:22,109
and they're both wearing
Reeboks.

133
00:02:22,150 --> 00:02:26,348
One is going, "Ree."
The other is going, "Bok."

134
00:02:26,387 --> 00:02:28,912
Reebok, Reebok.

135
00:02:28,956 --> 00:02:31,948
That's moronic, moronic.

136
00:02:31,993 --> 00:02:34,052
-[Sighs]
-[Squeaks]

137
00:02:34,095 --> 00:02:36,757
-I got it.
-Imagine my excitement.

138
00:02:36,797 --> 00:02:38,822
Wait. OK. Picture this.

139
00:02:38,866 --> 00:02:42,063
You have girls at a party,
girls on the soccer field...

140
00:02:42,103 --> 00:02:43,798
girls at a concert...

141
00:02:43,838 --> 00:02:45,328
all wearing Reebok.

142
00:02:45,373 --> 00:02:47,341
And the tag line?

143
00:02:47,375 --> 00:02:50,503
For girls who choose to move.

144
00:02:51,979 --> 00:02:53,344
MAN SINGING: Yeah, baby

145
00:02:53,381 --> 00:02:54,507
What do you think?

146
00:02:54,549 --> 00:02:55,743
I think the wheatgrass...

147
00:02:55,783 --> 00:02:57,410
has finally gone
to Higgins's head...

148
00:02:57,451 --> 00:02:59,146
for putting you on the team.

149
00:02:59,187 --> 00:03:00,313
You liked it that much?

150
00:03:00,354 --> 00:03:04,154
Look, I've worked
at this office for five years.

151
00:03:04,192 --> 00:03:07,753
I've got seniority on you.
This should be my account.

152
00:03:07,795 --> 00:03:10,320
You don't like me very much,
do you?

153
00:03:10,364 --> 00:03:13,197
Brilliant deduction, Scooby.

154
00:03:13,234 --> 00:03:18,001
Now let's get back to work and
come up with some good ideas.

155
00:03:21,242 --> 00:03:22,766
AL GREEN SINGING:
Hey, didn't go for that

156
00:03:22,810 --> 00:03:25,040
It's a natural fact

157
00:03:25,079 --> 00:03:26,478
Now I wanna come back

158
00:03:26,514 --> 00:03:29,506
Won't you show me
where it's at

159
00:03:29,550 --> 00:03:32,144
KEVIN SINGING: Where it's at

160
00:03:32,186 --> 00:03:34,347
I'm so tired ofbeing alone

161
00:03:34,388 --> 00:03:36,948
I'm so tired of on my own

162
00:03:36,991 --> 00:03:39,289
Won't you help me, girl

163
00:03:39,327 --> 00:03:44,390
Just as soon as you can

164
00:03:44,432 --> 00:03:46,730
AL GREEN:
Yeah, I guess you know

165
00:03:46,767 --> 00:03:50,066
That I love you so

166
00:03:50,104 --> 00:03:51,537
Sorry.

167
00:03:51,572 --> 00:03:54,700
AL GREEN:
You don't want me no more

168
00:03:54,742 --> 00:03:56,642
[Turns off music]

169
00:03:56,677 --> 00:03:59,305
ABBEY: I Can't Next to You.

170
00:04:02,550 --> 00:04:03,676
KEVIN: Excuse me?

171
00:04:03,718 --> 00:04:06,983
I'm So Tired ofBeing Alone
is a great AI Green song...

172
00:04:07,021 --> 00:04:08,318
but I Can't Get Next to You...

173
00:04:08,356 --> 00:04:10,551
seems a little more appropriate
right now.

174
00:04:10,591 --> 00:04:12,855
And why's that?

175
00:04:12,893 --> 00:04:16,659
Because
I can't get next to you.

176
00:04:16,697 --> 00:04:17,857
Oh.

177
00:04:22,536 --> 00:04:25,334
ABBEY: Ahem. Thanks.

178
00:04:30,244 --> 00:04:32,212
Ahem.

179
00:04:32,246 --> 00:04:34,441
I enjoyed your performance.

180
00:04:34,482 --> 00:04:37,280
Thanks.

181
00:04:37,318 --> 00:04:39,218
AI Green
helps me clear my head.

182
00:04:39,253 --> 00:04:41,847
It's a mental thing.

183
00:04:41,889 --> 00:04:43,083
Yikes.

184
00:04:43,124 --> 00:04:45,285
I hear he's playing at
the Opera House in two weeks.

185
00:04:45,326 --> 00:04:47,123
Maybe he's looking
for an opening act.

186
00:04:47,161 --> 00:04:48,719
You like the Reverend?

187
00:04:48,763 --> 00:04:51,960
[Laughs] My mom was listening
to Love and Happiness...

188
00:04:51,999 --> 00:04:53,261
when she was in labor with me.

189
00:04:53,301 --> 00:04:57,795
I think he's...
definitely in my soul. Ha ha.

190
00:05:00,608 --> 00:05:02,769
So...

191
00:05:02,810 --> 00:05:05,904
what do you do besides approach
strange men on the "L"?

192
00:05:07,315 --> 00:05:09,249
I go to school--grad school.

193
00:05:09,283 --> 00:05:11,274
-What do you study?
-Archeology.

194
00:05:11,319 --> 00:05:12,445
Archeology.

195
00:05:12,486 --> 00:05:13,612
What do you do...

196
00:05:13,654 --> 00:05:15,417
besides serenade
strange people on the "L"?

197
00:05:15,456 --> 00:05:18,983
Oh, wait. Wait, wait.
Let me guess.

198
00:05:19,026 --> 00:05:21,995
You are an ad man.

199
00:05:23,397 --> 00:05:24,887
Now, how did you do that?

200
00:05:24,932 --> 00:05:28,265
It's stitched on your bag.

201
00:05:28,302 --> 00:05:30,293
[Laughs]

202
00:05:32,606 --> 00:05:34,130
Have you done anything
I might've seen?

203
00:05:34,175 --> 00:05:37,736
I don't know. Uh...

204
00:05:37,778 --> 00:05:40,178
I had a hand in the Pop Secret
popcorn campaign.

205
00:05:40,214 --> 00:05:42,182
[Sings]
Butter makes it better, baby

206
00:05:42,216 --> 00:05:45,913
That's it. That's me.
I actually wrote that.

207
00:05:45,953 --> 00:05:48,251
So now when I go to Wrigley
and root for the Cubbies...

208
00:05:48,289 --> 00:05:50,484
I can look up at the big
Pop Secret billboard...

209
00:05:50,524 --> 00:05:51,650
and think of you.

210
00:05:51,692 --> 00:05:54,160
-You're a Cubs fan?
-Heck, yeah. Born and raised.

211
00:05:54,195 --> 00:05:56,891
All right, all right.
Um, so, tell me.

212
00:05:56,931 --> 00:05:59,161
Tell me your best and worst
Cub moment.

213
00:05:59,200 --> 00:06:02,499
-Best--whenever they win.
-Of course.

214
00:06:02,536 --> 00:06:04,868
Worst--game five
in the '84 playoffs.

215
00:06:04,905 --> 00:06:07,669
BOTH: The ground ball
went through Durham's legs.

216
00:06:07,708 --> 00:06:10,176
That is the worst moment
of my life.

217
00:06:10,211 --> 00:06:11,803
Horrible.
I was so depressed.

218
00:06:11,846 --> 00:06:13,336
I didn't even go to school
the next day.

219
00:06:13,381 --> 00:06:15,144
I cried.

220
00:06:15,182 --> 00:06:18,481
OK, most guys
wouldn't admit that.

221
00:06:18,519 --> 00:06:22,853
Yeah. I don't know why
I just told you that.

222
00:06:29,263 --> 00:06:32,960
DRIVER: Next stop, Adams--
Adams and Wabash.

223
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:34,297
That's my stop.

224
00:06:34,335 --> 00:06:36,269
[Laughs]

225
00:06:36,303 --> 00:06:37,861
Mine, too.

226
00:06:40,374 --> 00:06:42,069
After you.

227
00:06:42,109 --> 00:06:43,974
Thank you.

228
00:06:46,046 --> 00:06:49,243
So, tell me something that
you would only tell a stranger.

229
00:06:49,283 --> 00:06:51,979
Uh...whoo.

230
00:06:52,019 --> 00:06:55,420
I like to make paper airplanes.
My dad's a pilot.

231
00:06:55,456 --> 00:06:56,821
Really?

232
00:06:58,392 --> 00:07:01,122
Oh, wait.
Do you have a piece of paper?

233
00:07:01,162 --> 00:07:03,392
Yeah, sure.

234
00:07:03,431 --> 00:07:05,399
What, am I going to get
a little demonstration?

235
00:07:05,433 --> 00:07:08,300
Uh-huh. A little demonstration.
Thank you.

236
00:07:11,505 --> 00:07:12,904
That's very impressive.

237
00:07:12,940 --> 00:07:15,408
Thank you.
It's my own design.

238
00:07:15,443 --> 00:07:16,808
Ah.

239
00:07:16,844 --> 00:07:19,369
All right,
this is my favorite spot.

240
00:07:19,413 --> 00:07:22,348
-So, you've done this before?
-Many times.

241
00:07:22,383 --> 00:07:24,715
-You ready?
-I guess.

242
00:07:24,752 --> 00:07:26,549
Here we go.

243
00:07:26,587 --> 00:07:30,353
Strong takeoff. Smooth flight.

244
00:07:30,391 --> 00:07:32,222
Excellent paper airplane.

245
00:07:32,259 --> 00:07:35,524
ABBEY: Thank you.
Oh! Ha ha ha!

246
00:07:35,563 --> 00:07:38,589
KEVIN: But I think your
landing needs a little work.

247
00:07:38,632 --> 00:07:40,463
Yeah, a little.

248
00:07:40,501 --> 00:07:41,968
Definitely.

249
00:07:42,002 --> 00:07:43,629
All right, don't think
you're getting off so easy.

250
00:07:43,671 --> 00:07:46,367
-It's your turn.
-I don't know. Um...

251
00:07:47,741 --> 00:07:50,471
Let's see. Uhh.

252
00:07:50,511 --> 00:07:53,571
OK. You're totally
going to think I'm lame...

253
00:07:53,614 --> 00:07:57,573
but I can name
all the presidents in order.

254
00:07:57,618 --> 00:07:59,609
Washington, Adams,
Jefferson, Madison...

255
00:07:59,653 --> 00:08:01,621
Monroe, Adams,
Jackson, Van Buren...

256
00:08:01,655 --> 00:08:03,714
Harrison, Tyler, Polk,
